 
"MDI Material Dignity Infrastructure"

Key sources identified:

DiBella, Charles J. — Material Dignity Infrastructure / Building Material Dignity: An Urban Stabilization Blueprint for the Unhoused. Framework born from 30 years of lived street-level observation. Positioned as industrial manual, not policy proposal. Blueprint uses vacant commercial real estate post-collapse.

Padgett (2007) — Ontological security as central mechanism by which housing produces health. Wellbeing "arises from a sense of constancy in one's social and material environment which provides a secure platform for identity development and self-actualization."

Giddens, Anthony — Foundational ontological security theory. Routine as the anchor of selfhood.

Dupuis & Thorns (1998) — Ontological security and homeownership/tenure.

Henwood et al. (2018) — Ontological security linked to improved mental health and positive self-identity in youth exiting homelessness into permanent supportive housing.

Sanyal, Romola (LSE) — Dignity and Displacement: Precarity and the Politics of the Humanitarian Aid Infrastructure. Dignity as foundational human value requiring material conditions.

Fennell, Catherine (Columbia) — Subsidized housing, material/social legacies, collective care and obligation.

PLOS Mental Health (2025) — Older adults transitioning from homelessness: ontological security rebuilt only when housing is good quality, deeply affordable, and accessible. Three themes: (1) life pulled out from under me; (2) the system is broken; (3) social connection essential to rebuilding.

Housing Studies Association — Homelessness implies existential as well as material deprivation. More conceptual work on "homelessness theory" overdue.

Tandfonline (2023) — Homeless youth: conditions for ontological security unmet for prolonged periods during adolescence. Solutions require fundamental shift in political/economic systems.

Young people's developmental needs for kinship, belonging, and a relationally anchored sense of home are so fundamental that youth often prioritize them over retaining or accessing available housing.

They will leave shelter to be with people who know them.

What "Being Known" Does

Relational engagements, namely acts of remembering, witnessing, imagining, are what allow a person to become someone other than "homeless", resisting subsumption into the singular mass and becoming instead someone more-than-homeless.

When service interactions are predominantly experienced as objectification and infantilization, people opt out of the entire system in order to maintain a sense of dignity and self-respect. The material infrastructure becomes inaccessible because the relational layer is broken.

Identity Capital — The Operative Concept

Longitudinal studies show persistent struggles to shake off identities of homelessness even after housing is secured, pointing to identity capital (sense of purpose, self-efficacy, self-esteem) as a necessary layer alongside housing, education, and employment.

The Research Frontier for MDI

The term that needs theorizing:

Relational Dignity Infrastructure:
the human layer that makes material infrastructure inhabitable.

